        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/978a9f5060338657ddeb3781c6a3a2c8?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 350538,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 688653,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/688653/zw324",
                "reputation": 27205,
                "display_name": "zw324",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1371151608,
            "creation_date": 1371151608,
            "body": "<p><code>boolean[][]<\/code> is an array of primitives, thus although arrays are covariant, since a <code>boolean<\/code> is not an <code>Object<\/code>, it gives you an error telling you the cast is illegal. You might want to use <code>Boolean[][]<\/code>. Also note that unboxing and boxing does not work on arrays.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 17095424,
            "question_id": 17095367
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/nhcvo.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 255665,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 535871,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/535871/ted-hopp",
                "reputation": 235290,
                "display_name": "Ted Hopp",
                "accept_rate": 84
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1371151641,
            "creation_date": 1371151641,
            "body": "<p>You cannot do that. A <code>boolean<\/code> is a primitive, not a reference type. So while an array (or multi-dimensional array) of <code>boolean<\/code> values is itself an <code>Object<\/code>, it's elements are still <code>boolean<\/code> values, not instances of <code>Object<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you want to have an array of objects, you would need to box the <code>boolean<\/code> values as <code>Boolean<\/code> objects.<\/p>\n\n<p>Note that you can still write your code with loops without boxing:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>for(int i = 0; i &lt; b.length; i++) {\n    for(int j = 0; j &lt; b[i].length; j++) {\n        // Do something with b[i][j] as a boolean\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 17095436,
            "question_id": 17095367
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e4e7db55d21f6f6b33630cba7d4ee1af?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1088867,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1083951,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1083951/chris",
                "reputation": 5714,
                "display_name": "Chris",
                "accept_rate": 84
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1371151677,
            "creation_date": 1371151677,
            "body": "<p>Convert <code>boolean<\/code> to <code>Boolean<\/code>. Java can then cast <code>Boolean<\/code> to <code>Object<\/code> for you (as subclass and super class)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 17095449,
            "question_id": 17095367
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/t7odj.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 69149,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 201359,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/201359/%c3%93scar-l%c3%b3pez",
                "reputation": 236846,
                "display_name": "&#211;scar L&#243;pez",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1371151710,
            "creation_date": 1371151710,
            "body": "<p>Try this, noticing that the array of primitive <code>boolean<\/code> was replaced by an array of <code>Boolean<\/code> (same consideration for the other data types, e.g.: use <code>Integer<\/code> in place of <code>int<\/code>, etc.), which are object types and <em>can<\/em> be casted to <code>Object<\/code>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static void main(String[] args) {\n\n    Boolean[][] b = new Boolean[10][10];\n    // fill b with values\n\n    Object[][] multiArray = new Object[10][10];\n\n    for(int i = 0; i &lt; multiArray.length; i++) {\n        for(int j = 0; j &lt; multiArray[i].length; j++) {\n            multiArray[i][j] = b[i][j]; // no cast is needed\n        }\n    }\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 17095457,
            "question_id": 17095367
        }
